  "body": "## Description\r\n\r\nIn #1253 I noticed that several checks on single operations like voluntary exits and slashings require access to the wall clock state, which is constructed in a memory intensive way (cloned in the best case), used for a single check, and then discarded. A more efficient API would be something like:\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nbeacon_chain.with_wall_clock_state(|state| { /* do stuff with state */ })\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis could avoid cloning the state in the case where it's just the head (\"most of the time\").\r\n\r\nAlternatively, this could be mitigated by reviving the [validator-tree-ethdenver](https://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/tree/validator-tree-ethdenver) branch that uses a design similar to Proto's remerkleable to make cloning states cheap and efficient. This would likely have other benefits IMO, but would be a more major undertaking.",
